I'm 18 years old and have been a fan of the incredibles since I was 4. Anyway straight into it, the underminer did get away, very short fight but it was more about stopping the drill. The villain in my opinion wasn't very good quite trash. Syndrome is a villain he was amazing, it was all about stopping him and his ball which is also an amazing villain. In incredibles 2 though I disliked the villain. In the first film the locations are so cool, larva fight, city fight, Forrest fight. Oooo the red suit and green background, it looked amazing. I just rember the main location being a fany boat...meh. BETTER VILLIAN AND BETTER LOCATIONS NEXT TIME! I feel the silliness was abit over the top, with the baby on the boat. I wanted a emotional close call with a main character and a tremendous epic scene like in the first one when violet used her force field and Bob his strength to save the ball from crashing them from above

Title: Incredibles 2 Official Trailer
Comment: This is a movie I have been waiting for, for fifteen years and now it has finally come. Incredibles 2 is an awesome movie and does not disappoint. Disney and Pixar are great storytellers but why did we have to wait so long for this sequel? I was so pumped up for this movie I have not been this excited to see a movie since Avengers infinity war, and I will tell you one thing I was pleased, wish we did not have to wait so long. I loved everything about this movie my only problem was Screenslaver she could have been a better villain, don‚Äôt get me wrong she was good but could have been better. I wish they would have stuck with the Underminer being the main bad guy, oh well. I thought Screenslaver was cool for a moment until they revealed who she was, not going to say NO SPOILERS. But she was an OK villain not as good as Syndrome was. But anyways the story, animation, voice cast and directing was awesome. Glad they had the original cast back. I will say one thing Jack-Jack steals every Scene he is in. And my favorite scene is when he fights the raccoon. Hilarious, and I'm glad they delve into Mr. Incredible taking on parenthood. They did a lot more with the kids in this movie then they did the first. They did a great job on Jack-Jack‚Äôs Powers and how Mr. Incredible has to deal with it. Great movie and I hope we don‚Äôt have to wait another fifteen years for the third one We also get to see more of Frozone as well. If you have not seen this movie then I recommend you do. This movie is cinematastic. rating 5/5

Comment:
I just saw The Incredibles 2. It was pretty enjoyable, a refreshing and familiar throwback to days gone by.

I don't think it should be marketed as a children's movie however, as there are a few scenes that make me think that the PG rating wasn't quite right, such as the scene where Mr Incredible calls a coloured gentleman the N-word, and then then went on a 15 minute, explosive and explicit rant on how black people contribute the most to gun violence statistics in the United States. Yeah, not sure what the director was thinking.

Another odd scene was in the final battle between the Incredible family and the Underminer. The Underminer knocks over an embassy of a middle eastern country, and turns to screen and roars 'SYRIA IS ISREAL' , which was a little off, but only made stranger by the fact that he repeated it for 13 and a half minutes. Guess they just ran out of lines idk.

Speaking of running out of lines, the scene where Mr Incredible lynches Frozone didn't need to last 20 minutes. It was pretty graphic as well.

Overall, it was enjoyable, 7/10

Comment: Not nearly on par with the original, but it is good, but I think it's actually pretty forgettable. This movie doesn't offer anything new. In fact, for the most part, pretty much everyone is still facing the same problems: Mr. Incredible is struggling with balancing parenting life and superhero life, Mrs. Incredible (she has the best part in this movie), but Violet is still dealing with Tony (the same boy she was dealing with in the last one), Dash is having trouble in school, and Jack Jack is still just a cute baby (although he gets a few more laughs), and superheros are still illegal. This movie's biggest problem is it offers nothing new. Except the last movie had a cool villain - the villain in this one is LAME. They should have thought outside the box instead of having audiences wait 14 years for a watered down, carbon copy of the first one.

Title: Incredibles 2 Official Trailer
Comment: I know that everyone apparently thinks that The Incredibles is a better film than the Finding films. I suppose, from a storytelling perspective, that holds true in many respects. But just because a film tells a great story doesn't necessarily make it a favorite of mine. To me, the universe and cast that I'm first introduced to has to mean a lot to me. The Finding films are about non-anthropomorphic fish who live in the ocean, which I love, seeing fish are one of my favorite animals, and I really don't like seeing them humanized, like in Shark Tale. Incredibles, on the other hand, is about humans with superpowers. Which just isn't anywhere as meaningful to me. Sure, the storytelling is good and the characters are well fleshed out. But the Finding films do exactly the same, and whether or not they do it as good as the Incredibles means nothing to me because they do it well enough, and in the end, that's all that matters. But there are other elements, of course, that make the Finding films more meaningful to me than the Incredibles. A huge part of movies is the music. The scores for the Finding films are easily my favorite soundtracks of all-time. The depth and emotion of the stories is conveyed so well through the music that it makes you just feel like you're there, with the characters, feeling their joy, sadness, fear, and any other powerful emotion the two films invoke. The music for The Incredibles, from what I remember, was just mostly fun action music. Now there's nothing wrong with that, I mean, for instance, everyone loves the Indiana Jones theme, but I just feel the music of the Finding films went so much further, that the music in the was often downright beautiful, and rightfully so, since they feature a universe and characters which mean so much more to me. Even the choice of instruments used in the score of those films was particularly intriguing, since they featured electronics as well as acoustics. In the end music, like storytelling, is a huge part of what helps make a film a masterpiece. Music can do so much, and one thing I've found makes it particularly powerful is if it makes you feel nostalgic. Which leads into my next point: the nostalgia factor. As I've explained before, I sort of grew up a lot between Finding Nemo and The Incredibles, so while The Incredibles serves as a reminder of an awkward time when I was transitioning into adolescence, Finding Nemo is a reminder of a simpler time that I would give anything to return to. So between that, the fact that Incredibles 2 is being released so soon after Finding Dory, and the fact that it's unclear if there will ever be a third Finding film, I can't help but be unhappy about this. I'm glad everyone who liked the Incredibles is getting what they want, but it's just not a film that brings on good nostalgia for me, if anything it brings on bad nostalgia, and like music, that's kind of a big part of what makes someone like a film. In the end, while Incredibles might tell a story better than either of the Finding films do, it doesn't have a universe and cast that I'm in love with, the nostalgia of a time I wish to go back to, and a soundtrack that mesmerizes and touches me beyond description.

Title: Incredibles 2 Official Trailer
Comment:
Who would say that Three months¬†following Syndrome's defeat, the Parr family - Bob Parr, Helen Parr, Dash, Violet and Jack-Jack - continue operating under their superhero identity, the Incredibles. After successfully preventing the villain Underminer from robbing Metroville Bank, the authorities become concerned over the level of damage caused by the incident. As a result, Rick Dicker informs the Parr family that his department's "Super Relocation" program is being shut down, forcing supers across the world to permanently adhere to their secret identities. Soon thereafter, Bob and Helen, along with family friend Lucius Best - the superhero Frozone - are contacted by Winston Deavor, a superhero fan, telecommunications tycoon, and owner of DEVTECH, who proposes a publicity stunt to regain the general public's support of supers.

Helen Parr, considered the least-destructive of the supers, is selected to undertake the stunt by openly fighting crime in New Urbrem, under her old identity of Elastigirl. As part of the plan, Winston provides the family with a new home, to which Bob offers to take care of the kids while Helen is away. During her absence, Bob discovers that Jack-Jack has various super powers, but struggles with controlling the family's infant. Seeking help, Bob takes Jack-Jack to¬†Edna Mode, a family friend and superhero-costume designer, who agrees to help upon seeing the baby's superpowers in action. Meanwhile, Helen confronts the Screenslaver during her mission - a mysterious villain who hijacks screens in order to project hypnotic images that can brainwash ordinary civilians.

After rescuing an ambassador from the Screenslaver‚Äôs clutches, she manages to defeat him, only to find that he is no more than a pizza delivery man, who has no recollection of what he did. While attending a celebration of the Screenslaver's defeat at the Deavor's, Helen realises that Winston is being controlled by hypno-screens within his goggles. Before she can alert anyone to this, Winston's sister Evelyn Deavor overpowers her and brainwashes her with a similar pair. Evelyn reveals herself to be the mastermind behind the Screenslaver - seeing supers as a threat to humanity's independence, she sought to undermine her brother's mission, and plans to brainwash the world's leaders so that they cannot re-legalise superheroes. Evelyn then manages to lure Bob and Lucius into a trap, brainwashing both.

Avoiding the same fate as their parents, Dash, Violet, and Jack-Jack, whom Edna had outfitted with a super-suit, sneak aboard the Deavor's ship to rescue their parents, as the world leaders meet for a hearing on supers. After freeing their parents and Lucius, the group reveal Evelyn's plan to the assembled leaders. A battle on the boat ensues, threatening to crash the ship into New Urbrem. However, the supers manage to stop it and Helen apprehends Evelyn when she tries to make an escape. The supers are thanked and the Supers Relocation Program is finally reinvoked, making supers legal once again.

is it just me, or is this trailer exceedingly harsh on men?

start with the first 20 seconds. Then the trailer goes on to promote Helen (elastigirl) as the representative of superheros in which ceremony she scolds Robert when he is surprised it is not him who will represent superheros, the presumed choice.
he then becomes exaggeratingly frustrated when he doesn't understand his son's moth homework. throwing a fit in frustration, quite boorishly too.
and then it shows him failing to be able to take care of his home.
Then the kids being heroic (and not Robert...)
Then Frozone's subgeagtion to his wife who doesn't want him away from home (now, I understand that it's a joke that carries from the first movie, but my thesis stands, still)
And then the last and best display of male emasculation:
the last words of the preview:
Fire Robert.
(yeah I know that there's a comma. But the words themselves are hilarious!)

Title: Incredibles 2 Official Trailer
Comment: Not excited at all, just depressed that instead of getting another Finding film we're getting this. The Finding films are my favorite movies of all time and it hurts that I'm going to have to spend at least 5 more years waiting to see some of my favorite fictional characters again. To make matters worse I can't find practically anyone who's excited at the idea of Finding 3, I guess because everyone's managed to forget Finding Dory. Which really, really saddens me. Finding Dory is my favorite movie of all-time, even more than Finding Nemo. Yet everyone considers it inferior because it isn't as epic as the first. Well, that's what Finding 3 could be, but no one even gives that a second thought! I don't want the Finding franchise to go out like this and have tried talking to Andrew Stanton about it on Twitter again and again, but he never answers me. Finding Dory is such an amazing movie, but I feel there's so much more for this franchise and that a third film could be amazing. Another part of why I think Finding Dory failed is because it came amid some bad sequels and horrible original films. The only good Pixar film during 2011-2015 was Inside Out, so anything that wasn't grade-A original content or a seriously epic sequel was going to fail. That's not how I want the Finding franchise to end. Finding Nemo and Finding Dory are amazing movies and it hurts that I have to wait for another sequel to them because of all the Cars, Incredibles, and Toy Story movies Pixar would rather throw at us. So I really hope that Finding 3 is amazing. I've been in a bit of a depression recently because there's no movie on the horizon for the Finding franchise. I really hope that will change soon. Pixar has 3 more original films planned after Toy Story 3 but I sure hope Finding 3 comes out in 2022. If it doesn't it better be because they're trying to make Finding 3 great. I know everyone wants an Inside Out 2 and I guess that would be fine while we wait for Finding 3 but I still really want Finding 3 to happen. Andrew Stanton dropped a whole entire subplot with the Tank Gang in Finding Dory and never got back to us fans on why he did that. I really, really hope this is because he's planning a sequel where they go to find them or something. There's also the potential storyline of how Hank lost his tentacle which was never explored and is a really good idea for Finding 3. Also we all want to see Bruce, Anchor and Chum again, I'm sure. And I hope Nigel and the school of moonfish make a reappearance. I just know it could be really good. But it's frustrating having to wait and the fact that we got a president I'm really unhappy with less than 5 months after Finding Dory came out hasn't helped me at all. I just feel miserable in the post-Finding Dory world and seeing a sequel to some other, less deserving Pixar film just makes me feel worse. And on top of that are thousands of people who are excited about it and completely forgetting Finding Dory, which really hurts. Why is everyone forgetting a great sequel? We should still be talking about Finding Dory, not this! 2017 has been a rough year for me and I really just want some hope that there's a future on the horizon for the Finding franchise. I want to see Dory and all the rest again, because they're such an important part of my life. I barely watched Finding Nemo as a kid but now I wish I had. These movies mean everything to me and the idea of them ending saddens me beyond belief. I want to be hopeful but practically no one talks about the third movie, and the few ideas I see for it are awful. Which worries me that it will be awful, but for better or worse I really think they should make one more. If it sucks than people will realize that Finding Dory isn't so bad.

Title: Incredibles 2 Official Trailer
Comment: I'm still pretty concerned with how the plot appears to be set up as. Robert and Helen basically giving the kids the exact same treatment in regards to using their powers as the first film feels like such a slap in the face to them after they survived an incredibly hostile and deadly island and also playing not insignificant roles in taking down the robot. I'm not saying that the government and general public should be 100% in favor of Supers coming back, but from what we've been seeing in the trailers makes the plot look like a retreading of the first film, except Helen is the lead instead of Robert. The company with Saul Goodman offering Helen work also gives serious deja vu to Mirage/Syndrome, so I'm really hoping they're a red herring for the real villain. I'm still going to see it opening week, but I'm also going into it with a healthy dose of concern.

Title: Incredibles 2 Official Trailer
Comment:
*A SHOCKING, NERVE-WRACKING THEORY.*

Warning: this theory has a startling ideal that, should the theory be true, take out the emotion and damage the full effect of the movie. Basically, possible spoiler alert.

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

So I realized a pattern between the canon villains in the Incredibles franchise. The villains include Bomb Voyage, (An unnamed villain briefly cameoed with a missile), Syndrome, The UnderMiner, and the recently revealed ScreenSlaver. I realized that none of these villains actually have super powers of their own, but instead are technologically enhanced. 
Bomb Voyage uses bombs, Syndrome has a variety of robotic and advanced weaponry, the UnderMiner uses a giant mining drill, and the ScreenSlaver seems to have the ability to hack into television and hypnotize civilians. The pattern is that they utilize technology.

Then, I realized something deeper, more worrying and shocking.

There is one character who uses technology to their advantage. Someone who has a strong liking for missiles, lasers, flamethrowers, electric fences, machine guns, you name it. This person also tends to be narcissistic and aggressive towards many others (often hitting them with a newspaper, might I add), with a lot of power and money.

AND HER NAME IS EDNA MODE.

Ok, it feels like a bit of a stretch, I know. But if Edna was the true villain of the Incredibles 2, she might also be the hidden identity behind the ScreenSlaver. Someone with an intense budget and a lot of dangerous technology, as well as access to top-secret government information such as Super Hero Identities. Plus, in the two seconds the ScreenSlaver is revealed, their scrambled voice seems to (in my opinion) have a hint of Edna in it.

In all honesty though, there is no direct evidence that Edna is the ScreenSlaver, let alone an actual villain. But if she _was_ a villain, she would most certainly be a _great_ one, and a very dangerous one.

Again, this is all a theory, or maybe even just pure speculation, and it might be a bit biased. So if you're willing to discuss this, I am open to ideas about this.

Comment:
Ironically, those who think elastagirl as the selected superhero for the job was the right one forgot 3 things:
1. This isn‚Äôt husband vs wife. There was a third guy, Frozone, in the background
2. She was selected by a man of a company to serve for PUBLIC IMAGE by doing suspiciously staged heroic acts! Wouldn‚Äôt it be more appealing if a woman was saving the day? It was a sexist image of another type, not that the man can save the day (or woman), but something more fishy. Anyone could‚Äôve done the job, but she was selected for reasons beyond our understanding, perhaps more gruesome than it appears. As a matter of fact, this movie could end with the family values being restored, the superheroes finding their own way out of getting their rights back, and defeating this CEO of this company, who is suspiciously capable of bringing the superheroes back into the spotlight, and may have different intentions. Like what happened in Cloudy With a Chance of Meatballs 2, the corporate appears like a positive force here, but we‚Äôll get surprised when they turn against us.
3. Mr. Incredible seems to struggle as a father after spending years working at a corrupt insurance company, and even longer as a superhero. He even needs Frozone to support him. That‚Äôs something Elastagirl has a problem with not doing, because she knows she does better. But here they seem to agree on their struggles, and know that these struggles are necessary for the rights of their children.

Comment:
I suppose this looks promising, but there are so many more interesting directions they could've taken for this.
Like, how about Jack Jack - and the rest of the family - growing up? How would their dynamics change? Wouldn't juxtaposing themes of aging amongst teens (Violet), kids (blonde boy), and parents/adults (...you know who) both aging themselves AND watching their kids grow up be far more interesting? Mixing all of that good introspective, family themed stuff Pixar usually seems content with with some cool super hero stuff would've been really fascinating.
Eh well. As long as the mom being the big job honcho isn't something that'll get a giant brown-nosed feminist agenda magnifying glass on it, I guess this is nonetheless fine.

Title: Incredibles 2 Official Trailer
Comment: Written and directed by Brad Bird! This will very probably be at the top of this summer's hit movies. The first one was _incredibly_ good and lends itself to being a franchise much more than other Bird stand-alone animated hits like _Ratatouille_ and _The Iron Giant_ that are very fully resolved at the end. I can easily imagine a sequel to _The Incredibles_ that is not disappointing at all and possibly even exceeding the first which is already a modern classic. They built a great world that will be fun to further explore and the themes of the original remain very fresh. I choose to believe Bird stuck to his early statements that he wouldn't do this sequel unless he had great ideas for it. I'm going to see this one on the biggest cinema screen in my area. As of now I'm going to avoid coverage of the film in order to remain spoiler-free.

Title: Incredibles 2 Official Trailer
Comment:
Not sure how this trailer's filled with "female agenda." How's the dad staying at home and taking care of the kids and household and mom going out to work a "female agenda"? Well, maybe, in the sense that its promoting breaking set in stone gender roles, but that is actually a step to gender equality, and there's nothing wrong with that. The world ought to know more how taking care of the household at the house and the family (women's traditional role) is just as valuable as having a job and providing for the family (men's traditional role); many people are becoming more appreciative of women's traditional role but we still have a long way to go. And here's the thing: sometimes (as of right now, it is certainly not a status quo) the woman of the family might just be better fit as the working person and provider of the family (when the woman's smarter, got a better education, has a better job, is viewed more favorably etc.) and in such cases the man should be able to accept that and take on the role of caretaker of the household and family, and there's nothing wrong with it because being a housewife/househusband is going to be just as tough and emotionally stressful as working and making money; it is just as a valuable and heroic act for the family when done well. 

Having a job and working is HARD! We all get that. Even most women know since they did have jobs before getting married or something, but men usually don't have any idea just HOW hard it can actually be to take on the "mom" and "wife" role. 

Taking care of the kids (meals, their homework, school projects and assignments, handing out lunch money, keeping their grades in check etc.) and her husband (checking on his meals, attending as his partner in certain gatherings for his job, making sure he didn't forget anything, keeping his suits and ties in order etc.) is NOT easy, and it's a good thing that some men are coming to realize it  and appreciate the women of the household, out of direct or indirect (but still fairly direct) experience, because then many men who are always so dismissive of women's contribution as moms and housewives might have a change of heart.

And because of all of this, although I have never once thought Mr. Incredibles didn't appreciate Mrs. Incredible's role in the family dynamic (not in the way that's too bad or disrespectful anyway), this role reversal would give him a chance to learn, grow, appreciate his wife maybe even more. Most importantly, this also gives him the chance to connect with his children. It's one thing to go and play sports with your kid during the weekend and occasionally help with his/her homework; it's a totally another thing to spend time with them 24/7 and listen to their needs and complains and giving a "yes" and "no" at appropriate times.

Title: Incredibles 2 Official Trailer
Comment:
Notable things in this trailer:

1. It seems like the movie will start with the Incredibles fighting The Underminer and they'll win, starting a conversation about whether superheroes should be brought back, but they'll be arrested afterwards (or threatened with being arrested). At 0:43 Winston Deavor shows a picture of the Incredibles with their hands up and a policeman pointing his gun at them while talking about his plan to make superheroes legal again. In the picture, Frozone's ice is also seen, which has likely been left there after the battle with The Underminer. This means Winston's conference seen in the trailer is held when the battle is over. Who I assume is Evelyn Deavor also holds a golden pair of scissors at 0:41, hinting at her being at an inauguration ceremony and possibly Winston too. 
2. Confirmation that the Parrs get this house from the Deavors because of Elastigirl joining their mission, which was previously revealed as part of the background information for an associated Lego set. The house likely features technology developed by them since the Devtech logo appears at 1:09.
3. Voyd will probably be an ally to the Parrs. Her power is to "create voids where objects can appear and disappear", and her signature colour appears to be cyan. This means that what we see at 1:45 is most likely Voyd using her powers to help the family.
4. At 1:49, only the children seem to be in the car. Maybe they're going off on their own to do something like in the first movie?
5. It appears that Violet can use her forcefield power offensively and create shockwaves (1:51)! This scene and the one where Dash rescues an old lady are at the beginning of the movie, since The Underminer's drill is seen in the background.
6. Jack-Jack can use more than one of his powers at a time. At 1:54 he catches on fire while turned into a monster. This could imply that the monster form is his only real transformation and he might be able to use all of his other powers while in that form.

Get hyped everyone!!!! 8D
